The TTL (Time to Live) field in a packet specifies the maximum time or number of hops that the packet can take before being discarded, preventing it from circulating indefinitely in the network. It helps manage network traffic and ensures efficient routing.

The TTL (Time to Live) field is used in networking to specify the lifespan or hop limit of a packet as it travels through a network. Its primary purpose is to prevent packets from circulating indefinitely in case of routing errors. Each time a packet is forwarded by a router, the TTL value is decremented by one. When the TTL reaches zero, the packet is discarded, and an error message may be sent back to the sender. This mechanism helps maintain network efficiency and prevents congestion caused by undeliverable packets. Additionally, TTL can also be used in DNS records to indicate how long a record should be cached by resolvers.
